I simulated an Ukiyo-e print entitled &quot;A young courtesan surprised to discover a cherry blossom in her sakazuki&quot;<br>
<br>
(Use the link below to view the finished work)<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm14.showMessage?topicID=6126.topic">pub25.ezboard.com/fpolyka...6126.topic</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
Fujiyo translated it as &quot;Sakazuki no naka ni sakura no hanabira wo mithukete odoroku wakai Sokushitsu&quot; and then later mentioned that she felt she could've done a better job. So my question for you is; how would you have translated it and do you think the title makes sense (in Japanese)?<br>
<br>
Oh, I almost forgot- bonus question! I'm looking for the Japanese equivalent of &quot;Because all surprises should be pleasant&quot; playing off the European notion of a pleasant surprise.<br>
<br>
